I once considered therapy after my dad died. One point I looked into was the fact that they don't care. Which is a good thing, because your friends who care, also might have some sort of bias or say the wrong thing because they know too much about your life circumstances. Or telling your friends certain feelings may make them feel differently. I don't want to stress my friends out with all of my baggage. Some might try to fix the problem when they can't actually do anything and now they feel stressed out too. All I need from my friends is to be there and hang out. I have my friends to get away from my problems.

I opted to not get therapy and I am glad I didn't. I did talk to a couple of people and vented my problems and they suggested therapy. Someone called to check on me a couple times. After the 2nd time I asked them not to call again as the reminder was painful. I would be enjoying my day, and the grief phone call came in. Well, my day is ruined now thanks. I know they mean well and some people need that, but I didn't. I also didn't want somebody taking financial advantage of me when I was in my most vulnerable state.

Been a year now since my dad died. I've been through all of the stages of grief. Denial was pretty quick. That was over after I talked to the cops. Anger was a few months. I had moments yelling in my car. My dad died because he took smoking back up, and hid it from me. He had a heart attack, wasn't even 60 yet.. I was proud when he quit and was pissed off because he made a bad choice. I think I skipped bargaining. No way to bring him back after all. Depression lasted on and off for a while. I think I got through that after I sold his house. Acceptance. He's gone, I need to continue my life.
